snippet.textDisplay:
"Severity'? Is that a joke? The billionaire owners, who threw money at the club are being fined, essentially pocket money! And they're banned from a competition almost all but a handful of clubs in England even get the chance to play in. I'm sorry, but that's utterly ridiculous to suggest this is anything but the smallest taps on the wrist (it's not even slap). And it clearly sends a message to EVERYONE interested in purchasing a football club that the cost of handing tens of millions to your newly purchased club, and breaking (the most pathetic) of 'rules' is absolutely acceptable.

So the question of whether one of the most successful managers stick around... it doesn't matter. As amazing as he is, like most of the successful managers he requires massive financing to 'build' his team, and as he's neither winning the league this year, and has so far not won the Champions League with City he's hardly irreplaceable. A loss for sure, if he goes, but City will, and rightly, continue to throw tens of millions of pounds into the club. Football clubs to billionaire owners are essentially like virtual teams to gamers playing videogames. Absolutely nothing matters in this 'entertainment' industry other than trying to be the most decorated/glamorous/prized of clubs, in order to help build bigger support and extract as much from its most dedicated followers as it can.

I think the 'punishment' is near on laughable. What City have done should be taken very seriously. The club's punishment (sorry fans!) should be actually be severe.


Football is an entertainment industry, and UEFA like any other organisation overseeing such an industry exist to appear to keep everyone on the straight and narrow and are ultimately a front to legitimise the industry!

Incidentally I don't blame City's owners for doing what they've done. They are getting away with it so they've proved that what they've done to get City where they currently are was the smart way to fast track a team. That is the extremely clear message billionaires looking to buy a hobby in the Premier League can get from this.

snippet.textDisplay: Guilty or not, UAFA did not consider the underlying consequences for this club and it's fans.  They are affectively trying to destroy  a club and it's legacy in mid build. My feeling is that they will have to reconsider this penalty  because the severity of it does not reflect the infraction. It's like giving someone a death penalty for smoking weed. The players and fans should not be made to suffer for accounting errors or sneaky tactics. The burden of the penalty should fall on the business by means of more severe fines. Banning a team of players for something completely out of their control is guilt by association and not justice.
